        <div class="col-md-7">
          <h2 class="featurette-heading">Two Shoe Merchants - 18 Children to Keep in Shoes</h2>
          <p class="lead">Just as farmers had large families to help with farm chores, the Roderer brothers put their children to work early in their shoe stores. They both had plenty of help!</p>
                    <p class="lead">My grandfather and his wife, Rosina, raised nine-children - Anthony J. (b 1894), Margaret R. (b 1896), Rose M. (b. 1897), George J. Jr. (b 1900), Bernard J. (b 1902), Loretta A (b 1905), Victor J. (b 1909), Lawrence C. (b 1910), and Mildred M. (b 1912). All five sons followed their father's vocation; although; Bernard later left retailing to become a Chiropodist (the profession we know today as Podiatry). His brother's family was about the same size.</p>
          <p class="lead">George Sr.'s first expansion was to West Third street where he oppupied a storefront in the same building as the Wright Bros. Bicycle shop. A.J and George Jr. worked there together until 1927 when a third store was opened for George Jr. at 1941 North Main street. A fourth store was established on East Third Street and managed by Bernard until he went back to school. The two youngest sons continued to work in the Xenia Avenue stare with their father until his death in 1931. At the time, A.J. inherited the West Third street store, George Jr. The North Main street store, and Victor and Lawrence the Xenia Avenue store. Dr. Bernard established his office in what had been the family residence, connected to the Xenia Avenue store.</p>
          <p class="lead">In 1949, George Jr. built and opened a new store at 2001 N. Main Street. It was one of the first shoes stores in Ohio to specialize in chirdlen's footwear. Within the next few years, he purchased stores in Xenia, OH (Richard Shoes, Sidney, OH (Swank Shoes), Hamilton OH, (Leigheit shoes), and Cincinnati, OH (Swantz Shoes); but he continued to operate these locations under their original names.</p>
          <p class="lead">We continued to operate a chirdlen's store until 1982, when we entered the adult comfort shoe business. In 1986, we built and opened our current location at 5500 North Main Street, specializing in shoes for children and comfort shoes for adults. My son Michael, the youngest of the fourth generation, joined the family business in 1989.</p>
          <p class="lead">I have been truly blessed to work with my father and  my mother, my uncle Victor, my aunts Rose, Loretta, and Mildred. They have all been role models for me. I have been just as blessed to work with my son.</p>
          <p class="lead">We know our shoes. We like w hat we do. And we think it shows.</p>
