          <h2 class="featurette-heading">About Our Logo</h2>
          <p class="lead">When George Roderer opened his store in 1906, shoes were not shipped to merchants in boxes as they are today...</p>
          <p class="lead">...Shoes were shipped in cartons, unboxed, and it was the merchants' responsibility to box them. The boxes were not sent home with consumers, but shoes were removed and bagged. The boxes were saved to be refilled as new mechandise arrived in the store.</p>
          <p class="lead">The family name surrounded by a diamond was the logo on every Roderer shoe box. We still use the logo today in our advertising and on our bags.</p>
          <p class="lead">In bygone days, the typical store was about 25 feet wide and 50 feet deep. Two rows of chairs back-to-back usually ran down the middle of the store from front to rear with a counter running from sidewall to sidewall to the rear of the chairs. Under the counter would be shoe maintenance items like shoe polish, brushes, laces, and maybe nylons. The inventory was exposed along the sidewalls in shelving from floor to ceiling. An average store would have maybe three or four thousand pairs.</p>
          <p class="lead">Today we depend on the visual differences of the various brand's boxes to help us locate merchandise. With an inventory circa 15,000 pairs, if all were in boxes that were identical, it might be hard to find the shoes we are looking for!</p>
